fields.name: Altenatives to verbs like and want

fields.text_one: I don't believe it - the photocopier’s broken ______ again!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to stop working"

fields.text_one: Nearly two months ago, thieves broke _______ while she was asleep and took all her jewellery.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to enter a building illegally with the intention of stealing"

fields.text_one: Firemen fought for hours to control the fire, which had broken ______ on Wednesday night.
fields.explanation: If war, fighting, fire, or disease breaks out, it starts suddenly.

fields.text_one: Did you know that Pat has broken _____ with John?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to end a relationship"

fields.text_one: Two dangerous robbers had broken _______ of jail and murdered a police officer.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to escape from prison"

fields.text_one: Going on holiday for a couple of weeks will ______ you good.
The house was a disaster. They _____ a terrible mess.
Have you _______ all the arrangements yet?
Great improvements in public health have been brought _____ by advances in medical science.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make something happen, especially a change or better situation”

fields.text_one: The exhibition is open to people of all ages, so bring ______ your family and friends.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to bring someone or something with you when you come to a place."

fields.text_one: Larry is a brilliant negotiator, and he's brought ____ some big deals in his time.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " to succeed in doing something that is very difficult"

fields.text_one: After Ben’s mother died when he was three, he was brought ____ by his grandmother.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " to look after and educate a child until he or she is grown up ”

fields.text_one: Why did you have to bring ____ the subject of money?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to mention a subject or start to talk about it during a conversation or discussion"

fields.text_one: It's important that you learn to relax more, or you're likely to burn (yourself) _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to work so hard that in the end you cannot continue working, "

fields.text_one: Gore had burnt _____ the house in order to destroy the evidence of his crime.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to deliberately cause a fire in order to destroy something "

fields.text_one: The children in the school yard were playing football, fighting, or simply running about to burn ______ all their energy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to get rid of unwanted fat or extra energy in your body, by doing physical exercise"

fields.text_one: Willie smiled, his cheeks burning ______ excitement.
fields.explanation: If you are burning with a particular feeling, you feel it very strongly

fields.text_one: She'd fallen asleep in her chair and the fire had burnt ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to stop burning because there is nothing left for it to burn"

fields.text_one: A group of animal rights protesters burst ______ the meeting and started shouting at the speaker.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to enter a room very suddenly, interrupting the people who are inside or giving them a shock "

fields.text_one: When I asked her what was wrong, she just burst ____ tears.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to suddenly start doing something” e.g. tears, laughter, song, applause, flames...

fields.text_one: Helen, our teacher, was bursting ______ confidence and energy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "have a lot of something, especially a particular feeling or quality, or to be full of people or things

fields.text_one: It was such a funny story - even the newsreader burst _____ laughing.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to  suddenly start to laugh or cry"

fields.text_one: It's all your fault!" she burst ____ angrily.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to  suddenly say something in an angry or excited way, especially when you have been trying to avoid saying anything"

fields.text_one: You don't have to buy _____ the 'If you have a bigger house, you have a better life’ theory.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to completely accept an idea or belief and allow it to influence you:"

fields.text_one: In the US employers tried to buy ____ the unions by offering them higher and higher wage settlements.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to pay someone money or give them something that they want, in order to stop them causing trouble or threatening you"

fields.text_one: After the war, he bought ______ his brother Bill 's interest in the machine shop.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to buy someone’s share of a business or property that you previously owned together, so that you own all of it"

fields.text_one: People are buying _____ stocks of food in case the storm hits their area.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to quickly buy as much as you can of something, especially because there is not a lot available, or because you think you can make money from it."

fields.text_one: We'd better buy _____ some more beer for the party.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to buy  a large amount of something,  especially food or drink, because you may need a lot for a special occasion or it may become difficult to obtain"

fields.text_one: Is it all right if I call ______  again some time next week?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to go to someone's house for a short time to visit them."

fields.text_one: The company was facing a financial crisis, and the situation called _____ some tough decisions.
fields.explanation: If something calls for a particular ability, quality, or action that is what it needs or deserves

fields.text_one: Can you call ______ later? Mrs Cohen is in a meeting at present.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to phone someone again at a later time."

fields.text_one: Diana had seriously considered calling ______ the wedding two days before her marriage.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to stop an event that has been arranged from taking place, especially because of a problem."

fields.text_one: At 6am I called ____ Dr Minden, and he examined the patient.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to ask someone who has special skills or knowledge to come and deal with a problem."

fields.text_one: Mother seemed to have bought the entire contents of the store. "I saw so many nice things. I just got carried ______."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to become so excited that you do something you would not normally do, especially something silly"

fields.text_one: They carried _____ until all the work was finished.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to continue doing something."

fields.text_one: Extensive research is being carried _____, which will hopefully result in a cure for this disease.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to do something that you have organized or planned."

fields.text_one: Up to five days' holiday can be carried _____ from one year to the next.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make an official arrangement to do something or use something at a later time."

fields.text_one: Those long straight dresses are beautiful, but you have to be tall to carry them _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to look good in a particular piece of clothing or style."

fields.text_one: If you cast your _____ _____ to your school chemistry lessons, you may recall that a 'catalyst' is a substance that speeds up a chemical reaction.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to try to remember something that happened in the past"

fields.text_one: Meanwhile the bank has been casting _______ _____ a new chief executive.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to try to find someone or something, especially when this is difficult"

fields.text_one: It was time to grow up, time to cast _____ childish things.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to get rid of something because you do not need it any more, or because it is stopping you from making progress"

fields.text_one: If you were cast ______ on a desert island, do you think you'd be able to survive?.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to be left on an island where there are no other people, because your ship has sunk"

fields.text_one: He had been cast _____ by his family when they discovered that he was gay.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to force someone to leave a place, especially the place where they live, because you disapprove of them or something they have done."

fields.text_one: A new fitness craze from Australia called Body Pump is catching ___  the UK.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to become popular and fashionable."

fields.text_one: It had been a hectic week, and I spent most of the weekend trying to catch ___ ___ my sleep.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " do something that you did not have time to do earlier."

fields.text_one: Brian is returning from New Zealand for the first time in ages, and is keen to catch ____ ____ family and friends.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to meet someone you know after not seeing them for a period of time"

fields.text_one: Sorry I'm late - I was caught ____ in the traffic.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to be caught up in something, it stops you from moving or making progress."

fields.text_one: Footballer Paul McGrath admitted that his long-term knee problems are finally beginning to catch ____ _____ him.
fields.explanation: If something bad catches up with you, it starts to cause problems which you have been able to avoid for a period of time, but are now forced to deal with.

fields.text_one: For international flights you'll need to check _____ two hours in advance.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to to go to the desk at an airport in order to show your ticket and give them your bags to put on the plane."

fields.text_one: "Dinner's almost ready," Alice said, opening the oven door to check ____ the roast.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to find out if someone is doing what they are supposed to be doing, or that something is happening the way that you want."

fields.text_one: Let's check ______ the castle before we go back to the hotel.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to look at someone or something because they are interesting, attractive, unusual etc."

fields.text_one: What time do we have to check _______?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " return your room keys and pay your bill at a hotel so that you can leave. "

fields.text_one: I'd like Dr Harris to check you ______ once more before you leave hospital.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to examine someone to make sure they are healthy"

fields.text_one: When did life begin on Earth, and how did it come ______?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to happen, especially in a way that was not planned or expected."

fields.text_one: Jill came ______ her son s diary when she was tidying his room one day.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to find something or meet someone by chance, when you are not expecting to."

fields.text_one: Lisa's teachers always complain that she comes _______ as lazy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to seem to be a particular type of person or thing, or to have particular qualities.

fields.text_one: Why don't you come ______ for a drink after work?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " come to someone's house in order to see them.”

fields.text_one: It's been one of those days when problems keep coming _____ all the time.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a problem or difficulty comes up, it suddenly appears and you have to try and deal with it.

fields.text_one: We had been going out together for two years before the subject of marriage came ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a subject, name etc comes up in a conversation or meeting, it is mentioned or discussed

fields.text_one: Morrissey was really good at coming ____ ____ great titles for songs.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to think of an idea, plan, solution, or answer.”

fields.text_one: Women in the police force often complain that they come ____ _______ a lot of prejudice.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to be faced with a problem, or a difficult situation or person, and have to find a way of dealing with them."

fields.text_one: A lot of people came ___ ____ me and started asking questions.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to move towards someone or something until you are near them or next to them.”

fields.text_one: Nigel had been gay for years before he finally decided to come _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to tell people that you are gay, instead of keeping it secret."

fields.text_one: It’s hard work applying for jobs, and I am always worried that my age will count _______ me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if something counts against you, it is likely to stop you from being successful."

fields.text_one: If you're going to the beer festival this weekend, count me ____!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to say that you want to take part in an activity that other people are planning to do."

fields.text_one: Were going to the movies." "Count me _____," said Jennifer, as she sank into the couch, exhausted.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to say that you do not want to take part in an activity that other people are planning to do."

fields.text_one: Lee was a brilliant performer, and I was proud to count myself _______ his close friends.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to consider that someone or something belongs to a particular group, or to include them in the group.

fields.text_one: "How are you?" "Exhausted. I'm just counting ______ the weeks to my vacation."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to be waiting excitedly and impatiently for something good that is going to happen"

fields.text_one: The company has been told that it must cut _____ ____ research.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to reduce the amount of money that you spend, or the amount of something that you use.”

fields.text_one: It only takes ten minutes to get to the village if you cut  ______ the field.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to go across an area of land instead of going round the edge of it, because it is the shortest way”

fields.text_one: "Actually..."  Marc cut ______, that's not quite true.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to interrupt someone by saying something."

fields.text_one: I wish I'd cut ______ cigarettes years ago.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to stop eating, drinking, smoking etc , especially in order to improve your health or lose weight."

fields.text_one: I don't really enjoy being at home with the children - I just wasn't cut ____ ____ it!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if someone is not cut out for a job or an activity, they do not have the qualities that you need to do it.

fields.text_one: Then the engine cut _______ altogether, and we were stuck in the middle of the lake.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if an engine or machine cuts out, it suddenly stops working:

fields.text_one: When Sam’s father died last year, he was really cut ___ ____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to be very upset about something that has happened."

fields.text_one: We got cut _____ before he could give me his address.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if you are cut off while you are speaking on the telephone, you are unable to finish your conversation because the telephone connection is suddenly broken.

fields.text_one: Rumania was a Communist dictatorship, cut ______ from the outside world.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if the people living somewhere are cut off, they cannot communicate with other countries or people, for example because they are a long way from them, or because it is not allowed.

fields.text_one: The fan will automatically cut __ if the engine gets too hot.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a machine cuts in, it starts to operate when it is needed:

fields.text_one: They bought an old house and they're doing it _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to repair or decorate an old car or building, so that it looks much better."

fields.text_one: Don't do yourself _______!  You look lovely.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to criticize yourself because you lack confidence.

fields.text_one: I don't know much about his job, but I think it's something to do ____ the stock market.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to be connected with something in some way."

fields.text_one: There is a new computer that does _____  ____ the keyboard - you control it using your voice.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to get rid of something or stop doing or using something."

fields.text_one: I could have done ____ some help this morning.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to need or want someone or something."

fields.text_one: So England must do ________ two of their best players in the vital World Cup qualifying match on Saturday.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to succeed in dealing with a situation without someone or something that you want or need."

fields.text_one: The way I see it, they've done me ___ ___ three weeks' wages.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to cheat someone by not giving them money that they are owed, or something that should belong to them."

fields.text_one: I don't reckon she died of a heart attack - I reckon her husband did her _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to murder someone or attack them so that they are badly hurt.”

fields.text_one: On the wall was a polished piece of metal that did _____ a mirror.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if something will do for another thing, you can use it instead of that other thing.

fields.text_one: "I'm cold." "Well, why don't you do ____ your coat?"
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to fasten clothes, shoes etc."

fields.text_one: On Sunday afternoons, nothing can drag Jim _____ from sports programmes on TV.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make someone stop doing something, when they are so interested in doing it that they do not want to stop."

fields.text_one: I'm afraid some of the kids at school drag our daughter _____ with them.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make another person start behaving badly, like the other members of a group of people that you disapprove of."

fields.text_one: My parents are getting divorced, and I keep getting dragged ________ their arguments.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make someone or something get involved in an argument, war, or other situation that they do not want to be involved in."

fields.text_one: Both sides refused to compromise, and the negotiations dragged _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if an event or situation drags on, it continues for too long

fields.text_one: Teachers used to complain that Skinners children were dragged ____, not brought up.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a child is dragged up, their parents do not teach them to behave properly.

fields.text_one: In October the nights start drawing ___. In March, they start drawing _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if the days or nights are drawing in, it gets dark earlier in the evening”

fields.text_one: As soon as the train drew _____ and the doors opened, a mass of commuters flooded the station.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a train draws in, it arrives at a station and stops."

fields.text_one: Manchester United have huge reserves of  talent which they can draw ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to use part of a supply of something, especially money you have saved, for a particular purpose."

fields.text_one: Last minute questions drew the meeting _____ for another hour.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make something continue for longer than is usual or necessary."

fields.text_one: I'll have my lawyer draw _____ a contract for you to look over.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to prepare a contract or other official agreement, or a list or plan.

fields.text_one: Gareth walked much too fast for her, and got annoyed whenever she dropped _______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to move more slowly than the other person or people you are with, so that they move ahead of you."

fields.text_one: If you're in the area again just drop _____ and say hello.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to make a short visit to someone you know well, usually without making a definite arrangement before."

fields.text_one: I'm sorry if I dropped you ____ it, but she asked me why you weren't here.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to cause trouble for someone, especially by saying something that makes someone else angry with them."

fields.text_one: My wife usually drops the kids _____ at school on her way to work.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " to take someone or something to a place by car, especially while you are driving to somewhere else. "

fields.text_one: Too many students are joining gangs, getting into drugs, and dropping ______ after sixth grade.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to leave school, college, or university before you have finished your course."

fields.text_one: I picked up the suitcase and the handle fell _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something falls off, it becomes separated from something that it is joined to, especially because it is old or damaged.

fields.text_one: The subjects you can study fall ______ three distinct groups.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to belong to a particular group of things or people that is different from other groups."

fields.text_one: It's the story of a middle-aged doctor who falls ______  one of his patients.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to suddenly feel very attracted to someone and feel that you love them.

fields.text_one: You didn't think I'd fall ______ that old excuse, did you?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be tricked into believing something that is not true.

fields.text_one: My father had just died and everything was going wrong - in the end I just fell _______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if someone falls apart, they have problems which affect them mentally or emotionally and they cannot think or behave normally.

fields.text_one: It fell ____ me to give her the bad news.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a duty or job falls to someone, they become responsible for dealing with it or getting it done, especially when this is difficult or unpleasant.

fields.text_one: I hope she doesn't fall ___ ____ the wrong kind of people at college.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to become friends with someone or with a particular group of people after meeting them by chance.”

fields.text_one: The manager was falling _____ herself to be helpful.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to be very eager to do something, especially when this seems very surprising."

fields.text_one: Becker was depressed because he'd fallen ____  ____ girlfriend.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " to have an argument with someone and stop being friendly with them.”

fields.text_one: We'd accepted an offer of $200,000 for the house, but the sale fell _______ at the last moment.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if an agreement, plan etc falls through, something prevents it from happening or being completed successfully.

fields.text_one: Bruce has been flying ________ to Colorado every week on business.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : “to go somewhere by plane."

fields.text_one: They started talking about old times, and the evening just flew ________.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " if time flies by, it passes very quickly."

fields.text_one: Her sister flew ______ from New York to be at the wedding.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to arrive somewhere by plane."

fields.text_one: Whenever his girlfriend looked at other men, Joe would fly ______ a rage.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to suddenly become extremely angry or frightened.

fields.text_one: The old man flew ________ her in a rage.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to suddenly rush towards someone because you are very angry with them."

fields.text_one: Following _____ from the success of its Boboli pizzas, JS has introduced a new range of small pizzas called Bobolini.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: happen after or as a result of something else - used to say that two events or actions are connected with each other.

fields.text_one: Officials waited to see whether the terrorists would follow _______ ______ their promise to release the hostages.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to do what you have promised, planned, threatened etc to do follow through on a promise, plan or threat etc

fields.text_one: Soldiers are expected to follow ________ their orders without question.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you follow out someone's instructions, orders etc, you do exactly what they have told you to do

fields.text_one: The band is planning to follow ______ their new record with a three-month tour of the U.S.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to do something soon after you have done something else, especially in order to make sure it is successful."

fields.text_one: It had always been her dream to become a dancer. If only she had the courage to follow it _________!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : to do what needs to be done in order to make something happen successfully in the way that you want, or in the way that you have planned.

fields.text_one: Phil had broken his leg, but could still get ________ on crutches.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to be able to move around places without much difficulty - use this about people who are old, ill, or injured.

fields.text_one: What I'm trying to get ________ to you in this seminar today, is the importance of teamwork.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to succeed in making someone understand an idea or message. e.g.: get a point/message/idea across."

fields.text_one: I'm worried that if I stay off sick I'll get _______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if you get behind with your work, you have not done as much as you should have. e.g. to get behind with your work or studies.

fields.text_one: I knew Tom wanted to get ______  ____ his ex-girlfriend, and it made me feel very insecure.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to start having a relationship with a lover, husband, or wife again, after spending a period of time apart:.

fields.text_one: My Mum is always getting ____  me about my clothes.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to criticize someone in an unfair and annoying way.

fields.text_one: I'm tired. We got ______ really late last night.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to return to a place after going somewhere else.”

fields.text_one: I'd been unemployed since I left college, and it was really getting me _______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a situation gets you down, it continues over a period of time, making you feel increasingly unhappy and tired.

fields.text_one: They saw Edwin getting _____ the ferry and raced to meet him.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you get off a bus, plane, large boat, train etc, you leave it."

fields.text_one: We need to get some food ____ - I'll go to the supermarket on my way home.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to buy a supply of something you need and bring it home."

fields.text_one: After Christmas I'm going to get ______ ____ some serious job-hunting.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to finally make a serious effort and start doing something."

fields.text_one: Listen, I'll have Mike call you when he gets ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " arrive at your home or at work."

fields.text_one: I tried to read 'Moby Dick‘ when I was at college, but I just couldn't get _______ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “ to become interested in a book, film, piece of music etc, so that you enjoy it and want to read, see, or hear more. "

fields.text_one: She had married a rich man, and then used his money to get ____ ____ Chicago's social elite.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to become friendly with a person or group - used especially when you disapprove of this relationship,  e.g.: to get in with the wrong crowd.”

fields.text_one: She spent the whole evening trying to get ____ ____ Michael.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to start a sexual or romantic relationship with someone.

fields.text_one: -"How do you get ____ ____ Julie?" - "Oh, fine."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if two or more people get on, they have a friendly relationship

fields.text_one: There’s a meeting after work, but I should be able to get ______ by seven.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to succeed in leaving a place or a person, especially when this is difficult."

fields.text_one: Let's not even get _____it, mate. I'll break down crying - I miss my wife so, so much.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to start talking about a particular subject."

fields.text_one: He earns just about enough to get ___.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to have enough money to buy the things you need to live, but no more.“

fields.text_one: His wife got him ______ for playing away from home by coolly advertising and selling his Rolls Royce for £100.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to do something to hurt or embarrass someone, in order to punish them for hurting or embarrassing you.

fields.text_one: The kid was being so rude, and his mother just let him get _____  ____ it!.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : to not be noticed or punished when you have done something wrong.  ‘get away with it’

fields.text_one: "How did you get ____ at the doctor's?"
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used to ask someone about the result of their visit, examination, etc

fields.text_one: We should leave the President 's love-life alone, and let him get ___  ____ the business of running the country.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to continue doing something that you were doing before.

fields.text_one: We're both getting _____, now, and we can't travel about like we used to.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if someone is getting on, they are getting old."

fields.text_one: I've got a business meeting at 2.00 p.m. but I'll see if I can get ____  ____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to avoid doing something that you have promised to do or are supposed to do: get out of doing sth."

fields.text_one: She's just getting _____ a guy from Seattle. They met on vacation, fell in love, bought a house, and then it all went horribly wrong.

fields.text_one: Manchester United refused to give ____, and scored three goals in the second half to win the game.

fields.text_one: Karen was trying to look cool and businesslike but her face gave her ______ immediately.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to accidentally show other people how you really feel, or what you are trying to do, when you are trying to hide this."

fields.text_one: "Do you still have your old course books from university?" "No, I've given them all _____."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to give something that you do not want or need to someone, without asking them to pay for it."

fields.text_one: She gave ______ her job at the nursing home and moved to London.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " to stop doing something that you did regularly, for example a job or a sport."

fields.text_one: He'd been in a coma for six months, and the doctors had almost given ____  ____ him.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: " stop hoping that someone will improve or do what you want them to."

fields.text_one: There are several exams you can go ___ ___ if you want to improve your qualifications.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to compete in a competition, or to do an Examination.

fields.text_one: It's a difficult subject and there isn't time to go ____ it here.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to talk about something, especially in a detailed way. "

fields.text_one: How do I go _____ finding out about the different courses available?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you go about something in a particular way, you start to do it or deal with it in that way

fields.text_one: Several people at work have gone _____  ____ flu.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get a particular illness, especially one that you catch from other people and which is not very serious.

fields.text_one: Go ____ the black dress - it looks much better on you than the blue one.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : choose a particular thing because you think it is better or more suitable.

fields.text_one: It’s starting to rain. Do you want to go ____ or continue playing?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : to enter a building or room.

fields.text_one: Ed’s going _____  ____ a girl who is a lot younger than he is.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to spend a lot of time with someone and go to different places together, and have a friendly or romantic relationship with them.”

fields.text_one: I used to enjoy tennis, but I've gone ______ it a bit now.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to stop liking someone or something that you used to like."

fields.text_one: The band’s given several performances around the country and they went ______ really well.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "if something that someone says or does goes down well, badly etc, people react to it well or badly etc:”

fields.text_one: Jay wasn't very keen on the idea, but Jay went _____  _____ it just to keep everyone happy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to accept a particular idea or plan, or to agree with someone about something, especially because it might upset someone or cause trouble if you do not.”

fields.text_one: Twenty years had gone ____ since I last saw him.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if time goes by, it passes

fields.text_one: The match went ______, despite the terrible weather conditions.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if an event that has been planned goes ahead, it takes place, especially in spite of problems or opposition

fields.text_one: Parts of the castle here go ____ to the twelfth century.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something goes back to a time in the past, it was started or had its origin then.

fields.text_one: One of the witnesses has gone _____  ___ her original story, and now says she may have been mistaken.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to change what you said before, or claim that you never said it

fields.text_one: There seems to be a lot of noise – what’s going ____ in there?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "if something is going on, it is happening, especially something strange, unusual, or confusing.”

fields.text_one: I think I'll go  _______ and see Jim on my way home tonight.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to see someone for a short time, especially at the place where they live.

fields.text_one: Go ______ and let me get some sleep!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave a place or a person

fields.text_one: Dad went ______ to watch the baseball game.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: leave the place where you are and go somewhere else, especially in order to do something. Similar to go away

fields.text_one: He's always going ____ _____ how much work he's got to do.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to keep complaining about something, or asking someone to do something"

fields.text_one: "Don't you think I could borrow the car, just for once?" "Oh, go _____ then."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used to tell someone that you will agree to something that you had refused to agree to before

fields.text_one: The women all seemed to really enjoy their work, and went _____ it with great enthusiasm and cheerfulness.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to if you go at something in a particular way, you start to do it or deal with it in that way, especially with a lot of energy or enthusiasm.

fields.text_one: Do you think this meat has gone ______? It doesn't smell too good.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to if food or drink goes off, it is not good to eat or drink any more, for example because it has been kept too long, and it often smells bad.“

fields.text_one: We were having dinner when suddenly the lights went _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : if a light goes out, it stops shining

fields.text_one: We've been _________ a tough time lately, but hopefully things will start to improve soon.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means experience something, especially a difficult or unpleasant situation, or a period of time when a lot of changes happen.

fields.text_one: Rosie was very nervous, but all the arrangements went ______ really smoothly.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to to happen successfully in the way that you had planned.

fields.text_one: A bomb went _______ in East London in April last year, injuring seven people.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "if a bomb goes off, it explodes"

fields.text_one: Philip completely ignored what I said and went _______ eating.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue doing something without stopping or changing.  To go on doing something.

fields.text_one: Giving evidence in court was terrifying, but I'm glad that I went __________ with it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to do something you had promised or planned to do, even though it seems difficult or unpleasant, or you are no longer sure you want to do it

fields.text_one: Many restaurants go _______ in their first year.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a company or business goes under, it has to  close because it does not make enough money to continue.

fields.text_one: The boys went _______ and asked her for her autograph.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to walk until you are next to someone or something, in order to talk to them or do something.

fields.text_one: We really didn't like our neighbours when we came here, but they've grown ____ us now.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if someone or something grows on you, you gradually like them more although you did not like them much at first.

fields.text_one: At eighteen months my son was very shy, but he soon grew ______ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if children grow out of something, they stop doing it or are no longer interested in it as they get older.

fields.text_one: The kids have all grown _____ now and we want to move into a smaller house.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to change from being a child into an adult.”

fields.text_one: This generation has grown  _______ TV. They can't imagine life without it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to experience or do something a lot during the time when you are a child, so that it has a strong influence in your life.

fields.text_one: I wish you'd stop fooling around and grow ____!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start to behave in a more sensible, adult way, used about both children and adults.

fields.text_one: Sally put the chicken soup into bowls and handed them ______ to us.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “to give something, for example a drink, some food, or a piece of paper, to each person in a group.”

fields.text_one: The ring had been handed ____ to her from her grandmother.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: “ to give or teach something to someone, especially a younger member of your family, so that they will have it or know about it after you have died"

fields.text_one: All assignments must be handed _____ by Friday.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to give written work to a teacher so that he or she can check it.

fields.text_one: The organization hands ______ around $50,000 a year to young people with special educational needs.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to give something, especially money or food, to people who need it or for a particular purpose.

fields.text_one: On 7 October 1949 the Russian occupation authorities formally handed _____ power to the new East German government.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means : to give control or responsibility for something to another person, country, organization etc

fields.text_one: Hang _______! Where did she get all the money from?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used when you suddenly think of something that you want to say or ask and you want the person you are with to listen to you. Similar to hang on

fields.text_one: There’s no point hanging ______ this town any longer. Let’s get out of here.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to spend time somewhere not doing anything, for example because you have nothing to do, or because you are waiting for something or someone.

fields.text_one: It’s a beautiful painting. You should hang _______ it - it might be worth a lot of money.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep something and not sell it, give it to someone, or get rid of it.  Similar to "to keep a hold of"

fields.text_one: The cafe was a place where students and musicians hung _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to spend a lot of time somewhere or with someone, relaxing and enjoying yourself.”

fields.text_one: - "Shannon still seems to be hung ____ ____ Jeff."  -"Yeah, I guess it’s only been five weeks since they broke up."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be very attracted to someone and not be able to change your feelings about them.

fields.text_one: She said "I'll be there in a minute," and hung ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to end a telephone conversation by putting the part of the telephone that you speak into back in its usual place.

fields.text_one: In 1962 the threat of nuclear war hung ______ the whole world.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if something unpleasant hangs over you, it seems likely to happen or is going to happen soon and it makes you feel worried about what will happen.

fields.text_one: Everything hangs ____ the next game. If England lose, they're out of the World Cup.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: "to depend on the result of something in order to be successful.”

fields.text_one: Just hang ____ there, Mr. Mieuli, things will get better
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep trying even when you seem unlikely to succeed at something or the situation is difficult.

fields.text_one: The boat was going up and down, and we were all hanging ____ ____ dear life.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to hang on for dear life means to hang on very tightly, especially because you are very worried that you will fall. Similar to "hold on" or "cling on"

fields.text_one: Is it alright if I have a few friends _______ this evening?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to invite someone to come to your house for a meal, drink, conversation, etc. Similar to “to have around”

fields.text_one: What about tomorrow lunchtime? I haven't anything ______ then.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have an arrangement to do something. “To have a lot on” means “to be very busy”

fields.text_one: Joe is really upset. He's going to see Mum and have it ____ ____ her right now.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to end a disagreement or a difficult situation by talking to the person who you are angry with and telling them why you are angry.

fields.text_one: I can't see what you have _______ Alex’s friends. They seem nice to me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to dislike or disapprove of someone or something for a particular reason, for example because they have done something wrong in the past.

fields.text_one: Tim’s having you ______, Mary. Don't take any notice of him. He is not really a brain surgeon.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to pretend to someone that something is true when it is not, as a joke.

fields.text_one: We climbed on our horses, and headed ____ the hills.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to travel towards a place.

fields.text_one: As we head _____ the new millennium, we will see considerable changes in medical care.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start a period of time or a situation that is completely new and often difficult.

fields.text_one: Goldman praised his team of attorneys, headed _____ by Daniel Petrocelli.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  lead an organization, team, or project.

fields.text_one: Talks continued throughout the night in the hope of heading _____ the strike.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to prevent something unpleasant from happening.

fields.text_one: A policeman held out his arms to head them ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to make someone or something change their direction, by blocking their way.

fields.text_one: We were both in London when we heard ______ the accident.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get news or information about something or someone

fields.text_one: Please keep the letters coming, Mike. We so enjoy hearing ____ you.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get a letter or a telephone call from someone.

fields.text_one: -  “Do you know Piers Morrison?"  - "No, never heard _____ him."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have heard the name of a person, place etc before, so that you recognize it when you hear it again.

fields.text_one: Hear me ____ first, Jane, and then you can say what you think.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to listen to what someone wants to say, without trying to interrupt them.

fields.text_one: Jack offered to walk her home, but she wouldn't hear _____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to refuse to allow something, or refuse to accept someone's offer. Normally:  “won’t / wouldn’t hear of”

fields.text_one: This weird guy hit ____ every woman on our floor in the first week of college.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to talk to someone in a way that shows you think they are sexually attractive.

fields.text_one: The multi-millionaire has already hit _____ by threatening to take the newspaper to court.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize or attack a person or group, especially publicly, because they have criticized or attacked you.

fields.text_one: An angry Hurst hit _____ : "It was the worst match since I took over. Our team got what they deserved."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize something or someone strongly because you disapprove of  them - used especially in news reports.

fields.text_one: Frank took me out to dinner and we really hit it _______ straight away.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if  two or more people hit it off, they like each other as soon as they meet each other and become friends very easily.

fields.text_one: They tried various methods before hitting ____ the right one.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think of an idea or plan, especially one that is successful.

fields.text_one: "I know I've been a bit silly," said Claudia "but please don't hold it ________ me."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to feel angry, upset etc with someone because of something they did in the past, or to have a bad opinion of them because of something about them.

fields.text_one: Many students are held ______  at school by poor reading skills.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to prevent someone or something from developing or making progress.

fields.text_one: Can you hold _____ a moment – she’s just coming.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means (informally): to wait for a short time. It is used especially when, telling someone to wait a minute/moment, etc.

fields.text_one: The Council wants to buy the land, but the owners are holding ______ and refusing to sell.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to prevent change or prevent yourself from being forced to do something.

fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to delay something or someone, so that something takes longer or happens later than planned.

fields.text_one: You'd better keep ______, I don't want you to get my cold.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not go near a person, place, or animal.

fields.text_one: I've honestly no idea what happened - do you think I'd keep anything _____ if I knew?

fields.text_one: Teachers should offer advice to children in hospital on how to keep ______ at school.

fields.text_one: George used to play the piano, but I'm afraid he hasn't kept it _____.

fields.text_one: I've kept _________ several of my school friends, especially the ones that live near me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to write to, telephone, or meet a friend regularly, so that you do not forget each other.

fields.text_one: "What's the matter?" I asked. "You keep ________ of this," Charlie replied sharply.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not get involved in a situation.

fields.text_one: I tried to keep _____ political subjects to avoid any arguments.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to avoid talking about a particular subject, especially because it might upset someone.  Similar to “to avoid” or “to stay off”

fields.text_one: The album has made almost three million dollars in sales around the world, and people keep _____ buying it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to continue to do something or go somewhere.

fields.text_one: Young people often do silly things because they want to keep _____ with their friends.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to remain friendly with someone and make them continue to like you.

fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to relax.

fields.text_one: For some people it can take several hours before the effects of the drug kick ______.

fields.text_one: The landlord kicked me _____ out of my apartment as soon as I couldn't pay the rent.

fields.text_one: The football club made an offer for the thirty-five-year-old player, but it was knocked ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to to refuse an offer that someone has made. Similar to “to turn down”

fields.text_one: As Tracey was getting out of her car, a motorcycle nearly knocked her ________.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a vehicle knocks someone down, it hits them so that they fall to the ground and may be injured or killed.  Similar to “to knock over” or “to run over”.

fields.text_one: We could knock ______ this wall and have one large room instead of two.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deliberately destroy and remove a building or a part of a building.

fields.text_one: Knock it _____ , Liz! There’s no reason to drive like an idiot!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used to tell someone to stop doing something that is annoying you. Similar to: stop it!, cut it out!

fields.text_one: Louis knocked ______ his opponent in the first round by hitting him square on the jaw.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone become unconscious, for example by hitting them in a fight of giving them drugs.

fields.text_one: When I got home my wife started laying _____ me because I'd forgotten it was our wedding anniversary.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to criticize someone or something very strongly, especially in a way that seems unreasonable or unfair.

fields.text_one: The Geneva Convention lays _______ conditions for the treatment of prisoners of war.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to officially establish a rule or way of doing something, or say officially what someone should do.

fields.text_one: Thousands of workers in the auto and steel industries were laid ______ during the recession of the late 1980s.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop employing a worker because there is not enough work for him or her to do.

fields.text_one: I've already had to lay _____  £500 for the course fees.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to spend money on something, especially a large amount of money. Similar to “to shell out” or “to fork out” (both informal).

fields.text_one: The palace gardens are laid _____ in the same style as the ones at Versailles.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to arrange or plan the way something is organized.. Use this especially about a building, town, or garden, or the design of a book, magazine, etc.

fields.text_one: The boy’s mother has tried to stop him stealing, but she’s convinced it’s older boys who lead him _______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to encourage someone to do bad things that they would not normally do.

fields.text_one: He led her ______ right until the last minute: the wedding was arranged, all the guests were at the church, and he didn't turn up!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to deceive someone by telling them things that are not true, especially by making them believe that you love them.

fields.text_one: San Francisco will take on a festival atmosphere in the weeks leading _____ ____ up to the Super Bowl.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if a series of events or days, weeks etc lead up to an important event, they come before it.

fields.text_one: If a young child has problems with language, this may lead _____ _____ additional difficulties at school.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to cause something to develop or make it possible for someone to do something at a later time.

fields.text_one: Air-traffic controllers are worried that these proposals could lead _______ a major accident.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to cause something to happen, especially some time later.

fields.text_one: I think I left my credit card _____ at the restaurant.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not take something or someone with you when you leave or go to a place, either because you forgot to take them or because you left them there deliberately.

fields.text_one: Leave _______, Sethe - you're hurting me!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone to stop doing something, especially when they are annoying you.

fields.text_one: "I love you, I didn't mean to hurt you." "Oh, leave it _____, Mick- I've heard it all before!"
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used to tell someone that you do not believe what they have just said. Similar to “to come off”

fields.text_one: "What colour shall we paint this room?" "I'll leave that ____ ____ you," Jasper said.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to let someone decide and be responsible for something without trying to influence them.

fields.text_one: You've left _____ a zero in this phone number.
