fields.text_one: I tried to see him several times, but he shut me ____ by slamming the door in my face.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to prevent someone from entering a place, especially by closing a door.

fields.text_one: Mr Barnaby was just shutting _____ his shop in East London, when a gang of four armed men burst in.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to close and lock a house, shop, room etc that you own, temporarily, so that people cannot get into it or use it. Similar to “to close up”.

fields.text_one: When we left college there were so few teaching jobs available that a lot of us had to sign ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to claim the money given by the government to people without employment, because you do not have a job.

fields.text_one: How many people have signed ____ to go on the theatre trip so far?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to take part in an activity or a course of study, by writing your name down on a form or list.

fields.text_one: It was 8:58 pm and I'd been working hard all day so I decided it was time to sign ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to finish doing something, especially after you have been doing it for a long time.

fields.text_one: For security reasons, the company requires all visitors to sign ____ at reception.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to write your name in a book when you arrive somewhere that you are visiting, for example a hotel or an office. Opposite to “to sign out”.

fields.text_one: When Julie and her husband split after ten years of marriage, he signed ____ everything in the house to her.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to give property or a legal right to someone else, by signing an official document. Similar to “to sign away”.

fields.text_one: Kosar sat _____ two games of the 1990 season because of a broken thumb.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not take part in a game, competition, dance ere, because you are injured or tired.

fields.text_one: Do you mind if I just sit _____ today? I'm not feeling very well.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be present at a class, meeting, discussion, etc but only watch or listen instead of taking part.

fields.text_one: Yvonne will be sitting ____  ____ me tomorrow while I'm at the conference.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to a meeting, do a job etc instead of the person who usually does it.

fields.text_one: “I am willing to sit ____  ____ the Mexican leaders to discuss Fee trade,” Boice said.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to solve a problem, or to deal with something that needs to be done, by giving it all your attention.

fields.text_one: We had to sit _____ a whole day of boring talks about the company.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay at a meeting, performance etc until it finishes, even though it is very long or boring.

fields.text_one: People are starting to sit ____ and take notice about the dangers of genetically modified foods.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to suddenly start paying attention to someone or something.

fields.text_one: They sat _____ late into the night talking about old times.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay awake and not go to bed. Similar to “to stay up”.

fields.text_one: Just sit ____ and read the paper, I'll make dinner tonight.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get into a comfortable position and relax.

fields.text_one: Adrianne sat ____ the letter for a few days, unsure if she should mail it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be very slow at dealing with something, or to delay dealing with something because you have not decided what you want to do.

fields.text_one: Would you just sit ____ if it were your husband having an affair?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to allow something to happen when you should be doing something to try to stop it. Similar to “to stand by”.

fields.text_one: There's no hurry. I'm going to sleep ____ it, and tomorrow I'll decide what to do.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to delay making a decision about something until the next day or later.

fields.text_one: I suppose they're sleeping _____ the effects of last night's party.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sleep until you do not feel ill any more, especially after drinking too much alcohol.

fields.text_one: We usually sleep ____ on Sunday mornings as it is the only day that we don’t have to get up early.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sleep later than usual in the morning, especially because you do not have to go to work or school. Similar to “to lie in”

fields.text_one: A guy who's spent his youth sleeping _____ isn't going to find it easy to settle down to married life.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to have sex with a lot of different people without having a serious relationship with any of them.

fields.text_one: Mum, it is late and I have had a few drinks. Is it okay if I sleep _____ at Jim's place tonight?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to sleep at someone else's house for a night.

fields.text_one: Timothy Gedge had let the truth slip _____ while he was drunk.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if a remark or a piece of information slips out, you mention it without intending to.

fields.text_one: As the game went on I could feel our chances of winning the  championship slipping _____ from us.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means someone's power or their chance of success slips away, it gradually disappears.  Also means to die

fields.text_one: It was a serious lecture, but I was tempted to slip _____ a joke about the Clinton affair.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to quickly mention something when you are talking or writing about something else, without emphasizing it or saying much about it.

fields.text_one: She slipped ____  ____ her swimsuit and wrapped a towel around her.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to take off clothes or shoes quickly.

fields.text_one: Unless Manchester United slip ____ badly, they're sure to win the European Cup
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a careless mistake, especially when you are doing your job or playing a game.

fields.text_one: "We're here standing ____  ____ freedom against our oppressors" one demonstrator declared.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to support or defend a person, idea, or principle when they are being attacked or criticized.

fields.text_one: There are some interesting paintings in the exhibition, but one artist's work really stands ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be clearly better than other similar things or people.

fields.text_one: Schools are working with a network called SHAPE, which stands ____ 'Shaping Health As Partners in Education'.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to represent a word, phrase, or idea.

fields.text_one: Kate and Louie agreed to stand ____ their son Matt as he recovered from his drug addiction.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay loyal to something, or to continue to give someone help and support when they are in a difficult situation.

fields.text_one: There are lots of young men standing _____ on street corners, obviously without a job to go to.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stand somewhere and not do anything. Similar to “to loiter”.

fields.text_one: How sad for a child to start ____ in life with such a cruel father and a weak mother!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin your life or career in a particular way.

fields.text_one: After yelling at me for leaving the kitchen a mess, Mom started ____ Gary for coming home late.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin criticizing someone or complaining to someone about something. Similar to “to lay into” (informal).

fields.text_one: Arthur got into the car and started it _____ without any problems.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means to if you start up an engine, car, machine etc, or it starts up, it begins to work.

fields.text_one: We started ____ at 10 0 'clock in the morning, and reached Ambleside by 5 pm.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to begin to go somewhere. Similar to “to set off” or “to set out”.

fields.text_one: "I didn't start _____ to be a model," says Yasmin. "I did it once, and then more work just kept coming."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to intend to do something from the beginning. Similar to “to set out”.

fields.text_one: It was Saturday night and we’d decided to stay ____ late and watch the horror movie on TV
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to bed later than usual.

fields.text_one: This is a very unpleasant business, and if I were you I'd stay ____ ____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: not to become involved in a situation, activity, discussion etc.

fields.text_one: If you are expecting a baby, the best advice is to stay _____ alcohol altogether.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not drink, eat, or take something that is bad for you, for example alcohol or drugs.

fields.text_one: Sarah hadn't been out for a long time, preferring to stay _____ and look after Bradley.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to remain at home, especially in the evening. Similar to “to stop in”. Opposite to “to go out”.

fields.text_one: Phil had never stayed ____ without phoning me before, so I was really worried.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not come home at night, or to come home late, especially when someone is expecting you.

fields.text_one: I just stepped ____ to have a cigarette.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go out for a short time.

fields.text_one: In the second half, United stepped ____ the pressure and took the lead.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to increase the amount of effort, pressure etc, or increase the speed of something.

fields.text_one: Gary stepped ____ to calm things down between the boys.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to try to help or stop the trouble when a situation is difficult or there is an argument.

fields.text_one: If you don't step ____ it, we'll miss the plane!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to hurry and drive faster - used especially when telling someone to drive faster.

fields.text_one: Many people felt that the old King should step ______ and give his son a chance.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave your job or an official position, especially so that someone else can do it instead of you.

fields.text_one: I have some close friends who are prepared to stick ____ me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to support someone when they are in a difficult situation or have problems. Similar to “to stand by” or “to stick up for”.

fields.text_one: If a client doesn't agree with you, you must stick ____  ____ what you believe, but calmly and intelligently.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to defend or fight for something that is important.

fields.text_one: Marcia had said she would help, and she was determined to stick _____ her word.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to do exactly what you have promised to do.

fields.text_one: If you stick ____ for a while, I'm sure you'll find some sort of job.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay in a place, especially because you are waiting for something.

fields.text_one: You'll never be good at  anything unless you stick _____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: continue to work hard at something, even if it is difficult or unpleasant.

fields.text_one: The Foreign Minister will stop _____ in Paris on his way to the conference for talks with French officials.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay somewhere for a night or a few days during a long journey, especially in order to rest or visit someone.

fields.text_one: Lizzie stopped ____ all night on Saturday, my Mum won't let me do the same.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay out late at night at a club, party etc. Similar to “to stay out”.

fields.text_one: I want to stop _____ and see Tracy on the way home.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to visit a person or place for a short time, especially when you are on your way to somewhere else.

fields.text_one: On the way back home, he stopped _____ to look at a house he was thinking of buying.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop during a journey, for example in order to see something or someone, or to have a rest.

fields.text_one: I stopped ____ to watch the baseball and it went on until after twelve.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to not go to bed at the normal time and stay up late, especially in order to do something.

fields.text_one: When did Bryan take ___ golf?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start doing a particular activity or kind of work.

fields.text_one: A new baby will take _____ all your time and energy.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to use a particular amount of time, space, or effort.

fields.text_one: Yanto jumped onto the motorbike and started it. He took ____ it like a natural.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to enjoy and be good at doing something, especially the first time you try it.

fields.text_one: This was a nice place to work until she came to work here and started trying to take ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start to control what other people are doing, in an annoying way.

fields.text_one: How could you be so ungrateful! Have you forgotten how we took you ____ when you were homeless and looked after you?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to let someone stay in your home or in your country when they have nowhere else to stay.

fields.text_one: The bike ride will take ____ some of the loveliest parts of the county, including Belvoir Park Forest.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to include something - use this especially about the places visited on a trip, or the activities of a business.

fields.text_one: - You are such a good cook Paul?
fields.text_two: - Of course he is. He takes _____ his dad, don't you Paul?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be like your mother, father, grandfather etc, because you look like them, or because you have a similar character, or similar abilities.

fields.text_one: The tutor marked our assignments, and then took them ____ one by one, in front of the whole class.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to carefully examine what someone has written in order to consider and criticize the ideas in it. Similar to “to pull apart”.

fields.text_one: The advertisement looked perfectly genuine - a lot of people were taken ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be completely deceived by someone or something so that you believe a lie. Similar to “to be deceived/fooled”.

fields.text_one: Anyway, I did some radio interviews, but was quite taken _____ when I found myself on the front page of the New York Times.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be surprised or shocked, especially so that for a moment you do not know what to say.

fields.text_one: He had taken her ____ a working class girl. Now, hearing her accent, he realised his mistake.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think that someone is something that they are not.

fields.text_one: The next morning the kids went on a pony ride while I stepped back and took ____ some of the breathtaking scenery.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to notice all the details or qualities of something when you look at it.

fields.text_one: Two burgers and two teas to take ____, please.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if you buy food in a restaurant to take away, you buy it to eat somewhere else.

fields.text_one: I'm always so sleepy when I go to classes, I can't take _____ very much.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to understand and remember facts and information.

fields.text_one: "I don't love you anymore!" she cried.
fields.text_two: Immediately she wished that she could take it ____, but it was too late.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to admit that you were wrong to say something. Similar to “to retract” (formal).

fields.text_one: Why don't you take some time _____? You need a break.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to arrange to spend some time away from your normal work in order to have a holiday or do something else.

fields.text_one: My husband is very unhappy at the moment, and has been taking it ____ ____ me and the children.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to treat someone badly because you are angry and upset, even though it is not their fault.

fields.text_one: The plane took ____ into the night sky.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if a plane or bird takes off, it leaves the ground and rises into the air.

fields.text_one: She had an interview with a law firm in Glasgow and they took her ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start to employ someone.

fields.text_one: Cilla flopped down on the couch.
fields.text_two: "Looking after children really takes it ____ ____ you - they've got so much energy."
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make you feel very tired.

fields.text_one: Each year more and more amateur runners take ____ the challenge of the New York Marathon.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to accept an offer, opportunity, or challenge (something difficult and exciting that you have not done before). Similar to “to accept”. Opposite to “to reject” or “to turn down”.

fields.text_one: A group of us took ____ meeting in a bar called Harry's every day after work.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to start doing something regularly take to doing sth.

fields.text_one: - I'll cook you dinner if you like.
fields.text_two: - I might just take you ___ ___ that.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to accept an offer that someone has made.

fields.text_one: Digital cameras will eventually take ____   ____  conventional cameras.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to become more successful, popular, or important than something or someone else, and replace them as the most successful, popular, or important one. Similar to “to supersede” or “to replace”.

fields.text_one: I'm just going to take you _____ the business plan, and then I'll answer any questions.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to show someone how something is done by explaining all the different parts or stages to them, or by doing it with them. Similar to “to go through”.

fields.text_one: My father always explained things and never talked ____  ____ me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to talk to someone as if you believe that they are less intelligent than you are.

fields.text_one: Another City player, Alien, was shown a red card for talking ____ ____ the referee.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to answer your parent, teacher, manager etc rudely after they have criticized you or told you to do something. Similar to “to answer back”.

fields.text_one: Travel agencies have been talking the place ____ as a great new tourist resort.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to keep saying how good or successful something is, especially when you want to make other people interested or persuade them that is very good.

fields.text_one: I should never have let you talk me ____ this crazy scheme.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to persuade someone to do something by explaining to them why they should do it. Similar to “to persuade” or “to talk somebody round”.

fields.text_one: If you're worried about your work, come and see me and we'll talk it ______.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to discuss a problem or situation calmly with someone, in order to understand it better and decide how to deal with it.

fields.text_one: Kelly couldn't bear to think of him with another woman. It was tearing her ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone feel very upset and worried.

fields.text_one: Ben tore ____ his jacket and dived into the river.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to take off a piece of clothing as quickly as you can. Similar to “to rip off” or “to strip off”.

fields.text_one: Aldo read the letter quickly, then tore it _____ and threw it on the fire.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tear something made of paper or cloth into a lot of small pieces because you want to destroy it.

fields.text_one: For a long time Clarissa had been torn ____ her family and her career.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if you are torn between two things, you find it difficult to choose one of them or to decide which one is more important to you.

fields.text_one: Once he's in front of the television, it's practically impossible to tear him _____ _____ it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone stop doing something, when they are so interested in doing it that they do not want to stop.

fields.text_one: The twins looked so alike that only their parents could tell them ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you can tell people or things apart, you can see the difference between them, so that you recognize each of them and do not confuse them.

fields.text_one: Please don't tell _____ me - my parents will kill me if they find out!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone in authority such as a teacher or a parent about something wrong that someone you know has done – used especially by children.

fields.text_one: The two types of mushroom are very similar and it's difficult to tell one ____ the other.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: if you can tell one person or thing from another, you can see or realize the difference between them, so that you do not confuse them.

fields.text_one: Miss McHale will tell you _____ if she sees you doing that!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if someone in authority such as a teacher or a parent tells you off, they speak to you angrily about something wrong that you have done.

fields.text_one: I badly wanted the job, but I knew that my age would probably tell _____ me.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone less likely to succeed in achieving or winning something.

fields.text_one: A lot of these problems could be prevented by thinking _____ and taking action early.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think carefully and plan for what might happen or what you might do in the future.

fields.text_one: The speed at which the computer has changed American life seems even more amazing when I think _____ to my childhood.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think about things that happened to you in the past.

fields.text_one: "You're much too young to get married," my mother said.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to think carefully about a situation, problem, plan etc, and think especially about what might happen as a result of it. Similar to “to think through”.

fields.text_one: Lynn remembered the hotel clearly, but she couldn't think _____ its name.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to remember someone you knew or something you saw or did in the past.

fields.text_one: Everyone in the room was told to try and think _____ a new and exciting name for the book.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to find a new idea, suggestion etc by thinking about it and using your imagination or intelligence.

fields.text_one: Do you want to keep these catalogues, or shall I throw them ____?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to get rid of something that you do not want or need.

fields.text_one: The person selling the house may offer to throw ____ carpets and curtains as part of the deal.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to include more things with the thing that you are selling to someone, without increasing the price.

fields.text_one: The city has been making a great effort to throw _____ its negative image.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to succeed in getting rid of a problem or an unpleasant feeling that has been having a bad effect. Similar to “to get rid of” or “to shake off”.

fields.text_one: The smell was so disgusting, it made you want to throw _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to bring food or drink up from your stomach and out through your mouth, because you are feeling ill. Similar to “to vomit”, “to be sick” or “to puke (up)” (informal).

fields.text_one: I'm afraid it isn't much of a meal - just something I threw _____ while you were unpacking.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to produce something quickly without planning it carefully, using whatever things you have available.

fields.text_one: Mrs. Brownfield ticked us ____ for talking in class.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell someone angrily that they should not have done something - used especially when parents, teachers, etc. are talking to children. Similar to “to tell off”, “to scold” or “to reprimand” (formal).

fields.text_one: He told his driver to wait outside and keep the engine ticking ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if  an engine or machine ticks over, it works slowly and steadily. Use this especially to say that a car engine operates slowly when the vehicle is not moving.

fields.text_one: As the minutes ticked ____, the audience grew impatient for the show to start.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if time ticks by, it passes, especially when you are waiting for something to happen.

fields.text_one: Make sure that you tick ____ the jobs when they are completed.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to mark things on a list to show that they are finished or have been dealt with.

fields.text_one: Her brain was ticking ____ rapidly, as she was trying to think of a way out of her current situation.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if someone's brain or mind is ticking over, they are thinking about something, for example because they are trying to decide what to do, or they are interested in something.

fields.text_one: A lot of his emotional problems are tied ____  ____ his childhood.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be very closely connected with something.

fields.text_one: He said he loved her, but he didn't want to be tied ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop someone from being free to do what they want to do.

fields.text_one: Springsteen has released a new album to tie ____ ____ his current US tour.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if  a book, record, concert etc is intended to tie in with something else, it is intended to be produced or happen at the same time, and they are connected with each other in some way.

fields.text_one: Sorry, I couldn't see you earlier - I've been tied ____ in a meeting all morning.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be very busy, with the result that you cannot see someone or do something.

fields.text_one: Police said the two men tied ____ store employees before taking money from the cash register.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tie a person or animal to something using a rope so that they cannot move or escape.

fields.text_one: She spent the whole of our date talking about her previous boyfriends. Then to top if all ____, she suggested we go and visit one of them!
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used when you want to mention one final thing when you are talking about something, especially something very surprising (especially spoken).

fields.text_one: A local beer is available, starting at $1.50 a glass and topping ____ at $6.75 a pitcher.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if prices of something top off at a particular level, that is the most expensive price.

fields.text_one: We topped ____ the evening with a meal in one of my favourite restaurants.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to finish something that has been very successful or enjoyable by doing one last thing. Similar to “to round off”.

fields.text_one: Some more beer? Do you want me to top you _____?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put more drink in someone's glass or cup to make it full again. Similar to “to top off”, a top-up (noun).

fields.text_one: You can increase your monthly payments if you want to top _____ your pension.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to increase the amount of something, especially the amount of money that you earn, so that it reaches the level you want.

fields.text_one: The kids went outside and started tossing a football ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if people toss a ball or other object around, they throw it to each other for fun.

fields.text_one: His friends had been tossing ____ beers all day.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to drink something very quickly, especially Alcohol. Similar to “to toss down”, “to knock back” or “to drink”.

fields.text_one: - Who gets the last piece of cake?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if two people toss for something, they decide who can do or have something by throwing a coin in the air, and trying to guess which side will be on top when it lands.

fields.text_one: Some writers seem to be able to toss _____ a new book every few months.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to produce something quickly and without much effort. Similar to “to knock off/out”.

fields.text_one: They tossed ____ to see who would play first
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if two people or teams toss up for something, they decide who will do or have something by throwing a coin in the air, and trying to guess which side will be on top when it lands.

fields.text_one: I spent two hours trying ____ every coat in the shop, but none of them were just right.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to put on a piece of clothing to see if it fits you or to see if you like it.

fields.text_one: Jake turned up uninvited at the last party, and he might try it ____ again this time.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to behave in a way that you know is not acceptable, in order to see whether someone will try to stop you, or whether they will allow you to behave like that.

fields.text_one: The school is trying _____ a new method which claims to help children learn to read more quickly.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to use something for the first time in order to see whether it works well, or whether you like it.

fields.text_one: Simon isn't here right now. Can you try ____ in about an hour?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to phone someone or go to their house again later, after you have tried to phone or see them before.

fields.text_one: Joan tried _____ for the school basketball team but couldn’t get in the squad.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to compete or perform in front of a group of people who decide who should be chosen for a team, play, performance, etc.

fields.text_one: I felt very alone at that time - there was no one I could turn ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to someone for advice, sympathy, or help.

fields.text_one: The new company, Essential Computing, turned _____ £500,000 in its first year.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if a business turns over an amount of money, it makes that amount in a particular period of time.

fields.text_one: Rachel knew that Ross would be very worried if she didn't turn _____ for their date
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to arrive somewhere, especially when you are expected there. Similar to “to show up”.

fields.text_one: Don't worry about the interview, it'll all turn _____ fine. I am sure that you will get the job
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to happen in a particular way or have a particular result.

fields.text_one: I loved the house from the outside, but the decoration inside really turned me _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  make someone decide that they do not like something or are not interested in it.

fields.text_one: Crime fiction just doesn't turn me _____. I have never liked it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to interest or excite someone a lot.

fields.text_one: Rose finally agreed to marry Reg Potter, fifty years after she’d first turned him ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to decide not to accept an offer or an opportunity to do something. Similar to “to pass up” or “to reject”.

fields.text_one: It started off as a dream, but quickly turned _____ a nightmare.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to change and become a different type of thing or person.

fields.text_one: Well, I think I'll turn _____ now. I have to get up early tomorrow.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go to bed.

fields.text_one: When a member of your own family asks you for money, you can't just turn them _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to refuse to help someone when they ask for help.

fields.text_one: In just a year the firm has turned ____ from a £106 million loss to an £11 million profit.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if a business, school, economy etc turns around, it starts to become successful after it has been unsuccessful.

fields.text_one: I turned _____ the radio and listened to the six o’clock news.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a light, machine, or engine start working, or start the flow of gas, water, or, electricity, by pressing a switch, turning a tap, etc.

fields.text_one: Vincent was upset by Moore s critical comments. Why had the man turned _____ him?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop liking or supporting someone or something.

fields.text_one: Don't forget to turn _____ all the lights when you go to bed.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make a light, machine, or engine stop working, or to stop the flow of gas, water, or electricity, by pressing a switch, turning a tap, etc.

fields.text_one: One of the other gang members betrayed him and turned him _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to tell the police where a criminal is, or to take a criminal to the police.

fields.text_one: The Captain had been advised to turn ______, due to very bad weather conditions
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stop when you are travelling and start going back in the direction that you came from, especially because it is dangerous or impossible for you to continue.

fields.text_one: The Minister was accused of wanting to turn ______ the clocks to the 1950’s, when most women didn't work outside the home.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if someone wants to turn the clock back, they want to go back to the past, for example because they think things were better then or because they wish that something had not happened.

fields.text_one: I haven't found your watch yet, but I'm sure it will turn _____ sooner or later.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if something that is lost or missing turns up, someone finds it, especially in an unexpected place.

fields.text_one: Toyota’s new factory will turn _____ 100,000 pick-up trucks a year.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make or produce something, especially in large quantities. Similar to “to produce” or “to churn out”.

fields.text_one: The film was so boring that we turned ____ half way through it.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  change to a different programme on the television by pressing a button.

fields.text_one: Don't wait _____ for me. I'll probably be late.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to wait and not go to bed until someone comes back home. Similar to “to stay up”.

fields.text_one: Tammy hated having to wait ___  groups of noisy teenagers in her burger bar.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to serve food and drink to someone, especially in a restaurant.

fields.text_one: The store said they’d deliver the bed yesterday. I waited _____ all day but no one came.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay at home and wait for someone to arrive.

fields.text_one: We had to wait ____ for hours at the airport while they got the plane ready for take-off.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay in the same place and do nothing while you are waiting for something to happen, someone to arrive, etc.

fields.text_one: Jonathan asked her to wait ____ after the meeting.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to stay somewhere after the other people have left, for example in order to speak to someone about something. Similar to “to stay behind”.

fields.text_one: Several people walked ____ halfway through the film because they thought it was too violent.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave a performance or meeting before the end, because you do not like it or because you feel annoyed about something.

fields.text_one: Dorothy’s first husband walked ___  ___  her, leaving her with three children to bring up on her own.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave your wife, boyfriend etc suddenly and end your relationship with them.

fields.text_one: She can't just walk ____ after 15 years of marriage.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to leave a bad situation and not stay and try to make it better.

fields.text_one: Her husband walked ___  ___ them while they were in bed together
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to go into a room and see someone doing something that they do not want other people to see.

fields.text_one: You've got to stand up for yourself- you shouldn't just let other people walk all ____ you.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to treat someone badly, especially by always making them do what you want them to do without considering what they want. Similar to “to trample on”.

fields.text_one: Benn’s critics are saying that he's washed ____, and that his career in international boxing is over
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if someone is washed up, they are no longer successful in their life or their job, and it is very difficult for them to change this situation.

fields.text_one: Don't worry about the stain on the carpet. It'll easily wash ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means if something such as dirt or a mark on the surface of something washes off, it is removed by washing.

fields.text_one: Since you made lunch, I'll wash _____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to wash plates, dishes, knives, etc, especially after a meal. Note: In American English “to wash up” is to wash your hands before a meal.

fields.text_one: They ate pasta, washed ____ with several bottles of cheap Italian wine.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to drink something with or after food, or with medicine to help you swallow it.

fields.text_one: The water rushed down the narrow streets, washing _____ cars like matchsticks.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if water washes something away, it carries it away, usually with great force.

fields.text_one: The police were hiding in the bushes, watching _____ drug smugglers trying to cross the border.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb is used when you want to pay attention in order to notice something if or when it happens.

fields.text_one: Inter Milan are a strong team, and United had better watch ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be careful and pay attention because something bad may happen - used especially when warning someone to be careful.

fields.text_one: Watch ___ ___ the band's new record, which is climbing up the US charts.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to  be careful to notice something because it may be interesting, exciting, or useful – used especially when recommending something to someone.

fields.text_one: Can you watch ____ the children for me till I get back?
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to guard or take care of someone or something.

fields.text_one: Watch ___ ____ injuries while exercising. Always stop as soon as you begin to feel any pain.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to be careful to notice something or someone because they could be dangerous, could cause problems, etc.

fields.text_one: The mountain path has been worn ____ by tourists over the years.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means that if something wears away or is worn away, it become thinner and gradually disappears because it has been used a lot or rubbed a lot.

fields.text_one: Long hours of working in the hotel kitchen had worn her ____.
fields.explanation: This phrasal verb means: to make someone feel extremely tired.

fields.text_one: At the studio we were able to see engineers and technicians working _____ in the control room.

fields.text_one: The children were asked to choose their favourite poem and write it _____ in their best handwriting.

fields.text_one: Her car was written ______ in a terrible accident on the A34 in Oxfordshire.

fields.text_one: I'd be careful what you say to Stephan. He's got rather a ____ temper.
fields.explanation: If someone has a 'quick temper' they  lose their temper easily.

fields.text_one: Geoff is a bit high-____ and isn't very popular in the office.

fields.explanation: If someone is a 'rough diamond' they are of good character but initially at least appear impolite or uneducated.

fields.text_one: My father's a tough ____ and won't be worried about taking on a long, cross-country walk.
fields.explanation: A 'tough cookie' is a determined person who often succeeds in difficult situations.

fields.text_one: The unions are to meet the management to try and ____ the air after the recent threat of industrial action.
fields.explanation: To 'clear the air' means to try  to improve the bad feeling  between people.

fields.explanation: If you 'get your wires crossed'  you misunderstand someone as  you think they are talking about  something different.

fields.explanation: If someone asks you 'not to breathe a word' to  anyone they want you to keep something secret.

fields.text_one: I think you've missed the ____. We can't carry on ignoring the situation. We need to take action.
fields.explanation: If you 'miss the point' you don't understand  or appreciate an important issue.

fields.explanation: If you 'get off on the wrong foot' with someone  you make a bad start to a relationship.

fields.text_one: I wonder if you could put in a good ____ for me where you work? I'm thinking of applying for the a job there.
fields.explanation: If you 'put in a good word' for  someone you recommend or say  something positive about them.

fields.text_one: Don't beat around the ____. Just tell me straight what's on your mind.
fields.explanation: If you 'beat around the bush' you avoid  talking about the main issue.

fields.text_one: Your brother asked us to keep him____ about our holiday plans. I think he wants to come with us.
fields.explanation: If you 'keep someone posted' you  keep them up-to-date about something.

fields.explanation: If you 'spread rumours' you tell people stories  that may or may not be true.

fields.text_one: If you need any help just ____ the word and I'll be round immediately.
fields.explanation: If you tell someone they only have to  "say the word' you are offering to help  them immediately they ask for it.

fields.explanation: If you 'get something off your chest' you tell  someone about something that has  been troubling you.

fields.text_one: The builder was late again today. If he's not here at 9.00 tomorrow I'm really going to give him a ____ of my mind.
fields.explanation: If you give someone a 'piece of your mind' you  tell them directly how angry you are.

fields.text_one: I tried talking with Hanna but typically I couldn't get a word in ____.
fields.explanation: If you can't 'get a word in edgeways' you are unable to say anything because the other person keeps speaking..

fields.text_one: You know how stubborn my husband is, don't you? It's like talking to a brick ____!
fields.explanation: If speaking with someone is 'like talking to a brick wall' they don't listen to you or take your advice.

fields.text_one: I need to have a ____ in your ear about a sensitive matter.
fields.explanation: If you have 'a word in someone's ear' you speak privately with them to give them advice or a warning.

fields.text_one: His colleagues knew he was stealing from the company and finally someone blew the ____ on him.
fields.explanation: If you 'blow the whistle on  someone' you inform the  authorities they have been  acting illegally or immorally  because you object to their  behaviour and  want them to stop.

fields.text_one: You shouldn't go around pointing the ____ at people until you've got proof they've been up to no good.
fields.explanation: To 'point the finger at someone' means  to accuse them of doing something wrong.

fields.text_one: There's no point trying to deny it. You were caught red-____!
fields.explanation: If you 'get caught red-handed' it means you are  caught in the act of doing something wrong.

fields.text_one: What do you mean, it wasn't you who stole the money? You were caught in the ____.
fields.explanation: If you are 'caught in the act' you are seen  doing something wrong.

fields.text_one: In the end he decided to face the ____ and admit to defrauding the company.
fields.explanation: If you 'face the music' you accept the  consequences for doing something wrong.

fields.text_one: Andy was always getting into trouble but lately he's managed to keep his ____ clean.
fields.explanation: If you 'keep your nose clean' you stay out of trouble.

fields.text_one: The police have decided to give him the benefit of the ____ and let him go.
fields.explanation: If you give someone  'the benefit of the doubt'  you decide to believe them.

fields.text_one: He says he'll do all he can to ____ his name and fully expects the charges brought against him to be dropped.
fields.explanation: If you 'clear your name' you prove that you are innocent.

fields.text_one: The teacher said she's going to come down ____ on anyone arriving late for class.
fields.explanation: If you 'come down hard' on someone  you punish them severely.

fields.text_one: Once you have a bad reputation, people always ____ to conclusions about you for ever after.
fields.explanation: If you 'jump to conclusions' you take a  view on something before you have all the facts.

fields.text_one: Everyone knew he was stealing from the company but for some reason the boss turned a ____ eye to it.
fields.explanation: If you 'turn a blind eye' to something  wrong that is happening you ignore it.

fields.text_one: Be careful when shopping in that market. There's always someone who will take you for a ____ if they can.
fields.explanation: If someone 'takes you for a ride' they cheat you.

fields.text_one: That camera is cheap. Do you think it fell off the ____ of a lorry?
fields.explanation: If you buy something that has 'fallen off the back of a lorry' you have bought stolen goods.

fields.text_one: Now, I know one of you stole the money but who is going to ____ clean and own up?
fields.explanation: If you 'come clean' you admit to doing something wrong.

fields.text_one: Michele has been late for work every day this week but always gets away with it scot-____.
fields.explanation: If you 'get off scot-free' you avoid being punished for doing something wrong.

fields.explanation: A 'close shave' is a situation where something  unpleasant or dangerous nearly took place..

fields.text_one: I'd never done that kind of work before and actually spent the first few weeks feeling out of my ____.

fields.text_one: Not getting the job was a blessing in ____ as I now know that the company are about to close down.
fields.explanation: A 'blessing in disguise' is a good thing that isn't  immediately recognised that way.

fields.text_one: Why should we carry the ____? It wasn't our department who made the mistake.
fields.explanation: If you 'carry the can' you take the blame for something  that has gone wrong when somebody else is to blame.

fields.text_one: I was thrown in at the deep ____ and had responsibility for sales, although I'd never worked in that area before.

fields.text_one: The older people get the less likely they are to throw ____ to the wind.
fields.explanation: If you 'throw caution to the wind' you take a risk.

fields.text_one: We were sitting in the meeting when the boss ____ the bombshell and told us the business was being sold.

fields.text_one: I put a brave ____ on things but I was actually feeling quite sad.

fields.explanation: If you 'fight a losing battle' you try hard to do  something when you have no chance of success.

fields.text_one: I think I need to go home. I'm feeling a bit ____ colour.
